description.text:
This is a laser cut extension / riser for the typical UV nail curers, so that larger SLA prints can fit inside, utilizing the full build volume of the Peopoly MOAI SLA resin 3D printer.

Clad the inside of the chamber with aluminium foil or (better) aluminium tape. Do this also with the front cover.

Set your UV lamp on top. Put the removable bottom plate of the UV lamp at the bottom. The front cover can slide onto the little hooks.

This is designed for the particular UV nail curer that we have. The 4 holes in the top plate are for the round feet. Your design may be different, so adjust this for your particular unit.

title: Resin vat case - MOAI, also for Formalbs Form1

description.text:
We designed a case for the MOAI resin vat. This should also work for the Formlabs Form 1 vat

This is a handy option to store the vat outside the MOAI, and to remove the last bits of resin that are still inside even after pouring out the majority.

This is made from 3mm MDF, but could also be made from black opaque 3mm acrylic.

Its laser cut, and has an inner gasket so the bottom of the vat doesn't touch the bottom of the case, and an outer gasket so that the lid seals fairly well, ensuring that light and air can't really get inside. Gaskets are 2mm EVA foam.

Also, it has a removable corner raiser, so that the vat is slightly tilted when this is inserted, letting the last bit of resin flow into the lower left hand corner (takes a while), and then can be poured out more easily.

The lower frame around the vat is fairly low, so it's easy to insert / remove the vat once the lid is removed.

Additionally, the lower part or top can also be put over the vat inside the MOAI, e.g. if you want to leave the vat in over night.

Cut from 3mm MDF and 2mm or 3mm EVA foam. Instructions in the SVG file.

Or, if you like this and want to have me make you one (as a self assembly kit), let me know and we can make it for you. Cost: € 14 + shipping for MDF version, € 31 + shipping for black acrylic version (sorry, acrylic is really expensive. You could also spray paint the MDF version)

title: Printrbot PLUS v2.0 to 2.1 Carriage Conversion Kit

description.text:
Geday,  
I really like what Brook and the Printrbot team did with the carriage arrangement on the new Printrbot PLUS 2.1, but was saddened there was no conversion kit!  
Anyway, here is my homebrew one with my heavy duty extruder block.  
This extruder block has done hundreds of hours of printing with no issues whatsoever.  
I don't have a BOM for the whole lot, but it's coming soon. You will need a selection of M3 and M4 screws. I've used socket head cap screws but anything  will be OK.  You'll also need a spring for the tension on the extruder lever.  
Anyways, this bring the benefits of a DRAMATICALLY lighter carriage assembly (the only real weight is the bearings and the motor), along with mounting points for a fan to cool the filament in the area where the drive gear is. This tends to be a huge point of failure with the stock PB extruders.  
You can easily mount my LED light strip plates to the fan too (see my other designs).  
So when you disassemble your old carriage, put the LM8UU bearings into the printed bearing blocks, then bolt these on the inside of the carriage.  
Add your extruder to the top (the original laser cut wade's extruder will fit perfectly too).  
Add your belt to the belt mount and to the X motor side of the carriage.  
Mount the new carriage mounts to your carriage ends.  
And you're done. I hope this makes sense. When I get a BOM written it should be a bit easier, but if you're good with tools, you'll have NO problems working this mod out.  
EDIT 1 - Fixed spelling errors

title: Vorpal Hexapod HC-SR04 Ultrasonic Rangefinder Bracket

description.text:
This is an add-on accessory for the totally awesome Vorpal Combat Hexapod, If you haven't seen that yet, then this thing won't make sense, so visit there first:

  • Thing 2513566: Vorpal Combat Hexapod

I made this all open source and respectfully ask you to consider supporting the project. We successfully funded on Kickstarter with hundreds of kits sold, and now we have our own store. We have more than just the Hexapod electronics, we have all kinds of things useful for small robotics and other projects:
Vorpal Robotics Store with Hexapod Kits

  • IMPORTANT: If you opt-in to receive our store monthly newsletters you'll automatically be enrolled in a monthly prize drawing, first prize is a $100 store credit and there are lots of other smaller prizes too! Sign up for newsletters here:
  • Vorpal Store Opt-in for Prize Drawing

Why do I need this for the Hexapod?

This is a bracket that allows you to attach an HC-SR04 Ultrasonic Rangefinder Sensor to your Vorpal Hexapod for use with Scratch programming. This allows Vorpal to measure the distance (in cm) to the nearest object in the direction the sensor is pointing.

For example, you could implement obstacle avoidance as show in this video:

Ultrasonic Obstacle Avoidance Video

This sensor is pretty darn accurate, roughly plus or minus 1 centimeter in the range 2-180 cm for reasonably hard objects that reflect sound well. Very soft objects like pillows may not reflect enough sound to get a good result though.

Connections

VCC goes to any unused VCC pin on the servo controller (red pin)
GND goes to any unusued GND pin on the servo controller (black pin)
TRIG goes to Nano digital IO 7
ECHO goes to Nano digital IO 8

It is convenient to run some 15cm Dupont F-F jumpers for these connections down to the bottom of the accessory port hole (if you don't already have them there). Make sure you choose good colors for the wires to avoid confusion. Standard is red for VCC, black for GND, green for D7, grey for D8. I usually put a rubber band around the sensor wire bundle and leave it right inside the accessory port's wiring access hole, you can pull the bundle out to make connections when you attach a sensor, or just tuck it away when you're not using a sensor.

title: Shield for LightView Pro Flex magnifier lamp

description.text:
This design is specific for a great little LED magnifier light, the LightView Pro Flex.
This light is very bright and flexible -- it is easy to position for close-up work. The problem I had was when using it as a work area light the lower edge of the light is very bright and annoying. Also, when extended or turned the light can become not as stable as I would like.

So, I made a shield to block the side visibility of the light and a weight to provide more stability when the light is extended.

The fit of the shield isn't perfect but you can use a hot air gun to mold the back edges of the shield to fit better and to wrap around the area where the switch is located.

I used some redi-mix mortar that I had laying around to fill the weight cavity.

This is the lamp:
Brightech – LightView Pro Flex – 1 Ultra-Bright Magnifier Lamp
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01K10XA1O

The weight will print without supports.

The shield requires supports. I used S3D with 4 dense support layers at 80% infill and also 15% infill, 1 base layer, and no extra inflation distance for the standard supports. For the automatic generation I used 1mm support pillar resolution with a 50deg max overhang angle. With care, I could remove all the interior supports in one piece.

title: Smoke and overtemperature sensor for 2020 extrusion

description.text:
This is a more elaborated detection unit to be mounted on critical places in the printer like

  • Electronic box : detection of smoking/burning heated bed connectors, failing cheap PSU ...
  • Printing area (enclosed)

The unit has an FC22 print with a gas detection unit on it like the MQ135 ( suitable for detecting of NH3,NOx, alcohol, Benzene, smoke,CO2) , an NTC for overtemperature detection and a LED to signal fault conditions.
See detector specs here
Everything has a quite tight fit.
The holes for the NTC are placed so that they land on the 2 outer pins of the 6pin connector. Easy to solder like that!
I used standard network cable with one pair for the NTC, 2 wires for GND, 2 wires for Vcc, one for the LED and the remaining one for the Digital (or analog) out
Keep in mind that the detector module itself contains a heating element that draws 150mA (see specs). I didn't check the effects on PLA when mounted in the warm top section of an enclosed printer.

I printed this with a 0,6mm nozzle and 0,2mm layers in clear PC for the housing. The gas detector unit has also 2 LEDs on board : power on and alarm. These are visible through the housing.
Housing and mounting are screwed together using standard 16mm M3 screws. The bottom part has a smaller hole for the screws so they can be self tapping.

Modification 20170923
Cut out a hole on the bottom for easy access to the potmeter when using digital out.
Further documentation about this will be published on Github

You can find the schematic diagram build on an Arduino Nano and the firmware on Github

Have a look on Youtube too

description.text:
This is the 3d printed water driven eductor.

If you need capacity ratio 0.8 : 1 (0.8 part of driven water to 1 part of sucted water) - reduce nozzle diameter to 1 mm. But same way you will reduce pumping capacity. If you need so - post comment and I will add corrected STL model or print out current and insert into the nozzle small piece of pvc or ptfe pipe outer dia 3 mm, inner 1-1.5 mm.

IMPORTANT: need to create delivery head backpressure / backflow if you are using water to drive it, i.e.:
1) connect hose 20-30 cm to delivery end, OR
2) close 75-80% delivery end (by finger, plug, etc), OR
3) insert any screen or partition inside delivery end 1 cm in deep, OR
4) put eductor delivery end into the water at least 2 cm in deep (sometimes just touch water surface).

Venturi V1 (black on picture, STL file name "Venturi"): just testing model, but it also works.

Venturi V2 (yellow on picture, STL file name "Venturi V2"): upgraded model with better characteristics:
Suction ratio: 1.5:1 (1.5 parts of driven water required for 1 part of sucted water)
Suction capacity: 200 ltrs/hr @ driven water pressure abt 2.0 bars from 0.5 m suction head.
Maximum suction head: 10 mtrs of water @ 1.8 Bars of driven water pressure

Bonus:
To test it in your shower room you can find "Shower reducer" STL file - just connect it instead of shower head to shower flexible hose + use 10 cm of garden hose for eductor connection (find picture for reference).

PRINTING:
PLA was used for printing, ROTATE STL model VERTICALLY, delivery end to top.
For V1 add support (touching bedplate only) - it's for suction pipe.
For V2 no need any supports - print vertically, delivery end to top. Layer height 0.2 mm, nozzle 0.4 mm, 100% fill density.
Shower reducer to be printed vertically, thread to top - for better results, layer height 0.2 mm, 100% density.

title: Tap & Drill Alignment Tool for 20x20mm Extrusion

description.text:
Basics
A 3D printed tool to aid in aligning 20x20 extrusion for tapping and drilling. Basically to help with assembly of printer frame made with 20x20mm extrusion such as the HyperCube or my Cubeish! design ..

How it works
Slide the tool onto the 20x20 extrusion, then use the top hole for aligning the tap bit (for tapping the ends), or use one of the three M5 holes in the side to align for drilling when joining 20x20 together with a bolt/fastener. Plastic will melt with friction so only use the tool for marking position of M5 holes, then remove it or you can always print another one if you screw up...

Note All current 20x20 extrusion has a 4.2mm diameter hole along its length (in the center), if the hole is not 4.2mm, drill out the ends you are working on using a 4.2mm drill bit before tapping with an M5 tap...

Current Versions
Tool_TapDrillExtrusion_C.stl - Print Time: = 1:29 (Slight play ~1mm)...
Tool_TapDrillExtrusion_D.stl - Print Time: > 1:29 (Tighter fit and 5mm longer)...

I test built version C (Tool_TapDrillExtrusion_C) and it had a slight bit of play so I added version D which is tighter and also made it slightly longer for better precision. That's pretty much all you can do with plastic, it's time for a 3D printer that prints Aluminum...

NOTE: You will need to adjust the Z Reset Position in the Advanced Menu to 60 to have the right position for the gauge to measure. description.text:
I've remixed microphone holder by Tanato by complete re-draw it in OpenSCAD, so you may customize it as you want.

These particular STL files contain holder of 30mm long with inner diameter of 32 mm at the front end and of 29 mm at the rear end, mount base fits M8 nut (outer size between edges is 16mm).

Things added to the design:

  • adjustable base size to fit any nut
  • an inner diameter of the holder at front and rear ends may be set independently, so the holder may have a conical shape
  • adjustable length and thickness of the holder
  • I've added cogs for better traction at both sides of the joint
  • there is no necessity in a screw to put parts together - small axle my fix it

There is a parameter called "Print Expansion": if your printer makes parts slightly bigger (like mine), you could specify this expansion size in this parameter. It helps to fit a nut, an axle and a joint without filing or sanding.

Update 2017.09.26: combined all SCAD files into single one and prepared it for Customizer. Hope it works, let me know if you've got any problem with that.

Hope it will be useful.
